---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

const title = "Learning";
const description = "How I trained my judgment through sustained study and applied practice.";
---

<Layout title={title} description={description}>
<main class="writing-page learning-page">
  <header class="writing-header learning-header">
    <p class="eyebrow">Learning as method</p>
    <h1>Learning</h1>
    <p class="writing-intro">I follow where the questions get harder.</p>
    <p class="writing-description">
      Since 1992, I’ve returned to structured learning alongside my work. Not for credentials. For constraint. The goal has been consistent: sharpen how I think when decisions carry consequence.
    </p>
  </header>

  <section class="writing-list learning-section" aria-labelledby="formal-learning">
    <h2 id="formal-learning">Formal study</h2>

    <article class="writing-item learning-entry">
      <div class="learning-meta">1992–1994</div>
      <div>
        <h3>Oklahoma State University</h3>
        <p>
          Early study established the pattern. I was drawn to environments that forced clarity, even before I knew where it would lead.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="writing-item learning-entry">
      <div class="learning-meta">2005</div>
      <div>
        <h3>Stanford University</h3>
        <p>
          I brought my team at Yahoo! into a course focused on improvisation. The objective wasn’t performance. It was collaboration: learning how to build on each other’s thinking, articulate ideas in motion, and design without shutting down possibility.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="writing-item learning-entry">
      <div class="learning-meta">2016</div>
      <div>
        <h3>Stanford ICME</h3>
        <p>
          Coursework marked a deliberate turn toward data and systems. I focused on how decisions get made when information is incomplete, and how reasoning breaks under pressure.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="writing-item learning-entry">
      <div class="learning-meta">2017–today</div>
      <div>
        <h3>MIT</h3>
        <p>
          Sustained study through MIT programs has focused on design, AI, and decision systems. This work has been self-directed and ongoing, built on repetition rather than milestones.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="writing-list learning-section" aria-labelledby="field-learning">
    <h2 id="field-learning">Learning in the field</h2>

    <article class="writing-item learning-entry">
      <div class="learning-meta">Evernote</div>
      <div>
        <h3>User research</h3>
        <p>
          We observed preschool children fingerpaint to understand how people explore color without constraint. That work informed how palettes could behave in a digital product, shifting from rigid selection to fluid exploration.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="writing-item learning-entry">
      <div class="learning-meta">Yahoo!</div>
      <div>
        <h3>Team learning</h3>
        <p>
          Through improvisation training at Stanford, we practiced building on each other’s ideas in real time. It reshaped how I think about collaboration: systems should extend thinking, not shut it down.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="writing-item learning-entry">
      <div class="learning-meta">Civic systems</div>
      <div>
        <h3>Field observation</h3>
        <p>
          Work in election environments reinforced how systems behave under pressure. Procedures matter, but interpretation determines whether participation and trust hold.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="writing-list learning-section learning-proof" aria-labelledby="proof">
    <h2 id="proof">How it shows up in the work</h2>

    <article class="writing-item learning-entry">
      <div class="learning-meta">01</div>
      <div>
        <h3>Separate signal from output</h3>
        <p>I look past what a system returns and ask what the output actually means under real conditions.</p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="writing-item learning-entry">
      <div class="learning-meta">02</div>
      <div>
        <h3>Design for interpretation</h3>
        <p>I build for the human layer where uncertainty, escalation, and judgment determine whether a system holds.</p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="writing-item learning-entry">
      <div class="learning-meta">03</div>
      <div>
        <h3>Stay accountable when wrong</h3>
        <p>I treat failure as expected, not exceptional, and design systems that can be challenged, corrected, and trusted again.</p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="learning-close">
    <p>
      I don’t use learning to expand what I know. I use it to reduce how often I’m wrong in systems that matter.
    </p>
    <p>
      Learning is still active. Today it meant explaining equatorial storms and jet streams to my six-year-old.
    </p>
  </section>
</main>
</Layout>

<style>
  .learning-page {
    max-width: var(--content-width, 760px);
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: var(--page-padding, 3rem 1.25rem 5rem);
  }

  .learning-header {
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
  }

  .eyebrow,
  .learning-meta {
    color: #3e5a82;
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.14em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .eyebrow {
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .learning-section {
    margin-top: 3rem;
  }

  .learning-section h2 {
    margin: 0 0 1.5rem;
  }

  .learning-entry {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 8rem minmax(0, 1fr);
    column-gap: 2rem;
  }

  .learning-entry h3 {
    margin: 0 0 0.35rem;
  }

  .learning-entry p {
    margin: 0;
  }

  .learning-close {
    border-top: 1px solid rgba(62, 90, 130, 0.22);
    margin-top: 3rem;
    padding-top: 2rem;
  }

  .learning-close p:first-child {
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    line-height: 1.45;
  }

  @media (max-width: 700px) {
    .learning-entry {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      row-gap: 0.35rem;
    }
  }
</style>